text.tspan: First two indices correspond to a square on the board (the piece to pick up). For example, [0,0,:] represents the piece
on (0,0), or a1 in standard chess notation.
The third index corresponds to all possible moves from that square given any piece.
56 for queen moves + 8 for knight moves + 9 for pawn underpromotions = 73, the length of the third dimension
Both Leela and AlphaZero use a chess engine to calculate all illegal moves which can be used to "zero out" any
indices which represent an illegal move.
Simply a prediction of the winner of the game
A move in chess may be described in two parts: selecting the piece to move, and then
selecting among the legal moves for that piece. We represent the policy π(a|s) by a 8 × 8 × 73
stack of planes encoding a probability distribution over 4,672 possible moves. Each of the 8×8
positions identifies the square from which to “pick up” a piece. The first 56 planes encode
possible ‘queen moves’ for any piece: a number of squares [1..7] in which the piece will be
moved, along one of eight relative compass directions {N, NE, E, SE, S, SW, W, NW}. The
next 8 planes encode possible knight moves for that piece. The final 9 planes encode possible
underpromotions for pawn moves or captures in two possible diagonals, to knight, bishop or
rook respectively. Other pawn moves or captures from the seventh rank are promoted to a
For chess, there is a plane that represents each type of piece on the board, hence why P1 piece has 6 planes
(one for each queens, king, pawns, bishops, knights, rooks). Colour indicates whose turn it is currently to move.
Not sure what total move count or no-progress are for, not sure how they are represented.
